ilt around consumer products. But while papers provided a guide to individual upward mobility, they also fostered a climate of civic concern and responsibility. Charity campaigns and metropolitan sections painted portraits of distinctive, cohesive urban communities. Real estate sections and classified ads boosted the profile of the suburbs, expanding metropolitan areas while maintaining cities' roles as economic and information hubs. All the while, editors were drawing in new reading audiences-women, immigrants, and working-class readers-helping to give rise to the diverse, contentious, and commercial public sphere of the twentieth century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 22. Okt 2019) 0aAmerican newspapersxHistoryy19th century. 0aAmerican newspapersxHistoryy20th century. 0aAmerican newspapersxSocial aspects. 0aCities and townszUnited StatesxHistory. 0aCity dwellerszUnited States. 0aNews audienceszUnited States. 0aUrbanizationzUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aUrbanizationzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 4aCivic. 4aFeature. 4aJournalism. 4aMedia. 4aMetropolis. 4aMetropolitan. 4aNewspaper. 4aUrban. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG and UP eBook Package 2016-2019z978311063851608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018z978311063537940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226341477423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226341477.jpg  a978-3-11-063537-9  University of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  a978-3-11-063851-6  DG and UP eBook Package 2016-2019c2016d2019  aGBV-deGruyter-alles